.TH "leenfetch" "1" "" "Leenfetch 1.2.1" "Manual"
.hy
.SH leenfetch \[em] User Commands
.SS NAME
.PP
leenfetch \[em] a modern, minimal, and the fastest system info tool,
written in Rust.
.SS SYNOPSIS
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
leenfetch [OPTIONS]
\f[R]
.fi
.SS DESCRIPTION
.PP
\f[B]leenfetch\f[R] is a modern, fast, and highly configurable system
information tool written in Rust.
It displays system information alongside a distribution logo or custom
ASCII art, similar to Neofetch, and is designed for both terminal
enthusiasts and new users.
It can also fetch data from remote hosts over SSH and render it locally
in pretty or JSON form.
.PP
Configuration lives in a single JSON-with-comments file
(\f[V]config.jsonc\f[R]), with inline explanations for every option.
.PP
leenfetch can also accept \f[B]piped input\f[R] to render as ASCII art.
This allows users to display custom text logos via standard input.
.SS OPTIONS
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]-v\f[R], \f[V]--version\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Print version information and exit.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]-h\f[R], \f[V]--help\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Show usage information and exit.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]-l\f[R], \f[V]--list-options\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
List all configuration keys and accepted values.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]-i\f[R], \f[V]--init\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Create the default configuration file if it does not exist.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]-r\f[R], \f[V]--reinit\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Delete the configuration file and regenerate it with bundled defaults.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--config <PATH>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Load configuration from a custom JSONC file.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--no-config\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Ignore files and run with built-in defaults.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--ascii_distro <DISTRO>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Override the ASCII art distribution for this run (e.g., \f[V]arch\f[R],
\f[V]ubuntu\f[R], \f[V]debian\f[R]).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--ascii_colors <COLORS>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Override the ASCII palette (comma-separated indices such as
\f[V]1,2,3,4,5,6,7\f[R] or \f[V]distro\f[R]).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--custom_ascii_path <PATH>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Use a custom ASCII art file for this run.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--color-blocks <GLYPH>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Change the glyph used for the color swatch (default: \f[V]●\f[R]).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--battery-display <MODE>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Switch battery output between \f[V]off\f[R], \f[V]bar\f[R],
\f[V]infobar\f[R], and \f[V]barinfo\f[R].
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--disk-display <MODE>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Select disk output (\f[V]info\f[R], \f[V]percentage\f[R],
\f[V]infobar\f[R], \f[V]barinfo\f[R], \f[V]bar\f[R]).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--disk-subtitle <MODE>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Choose disk labels (\f[V]name\f[R], \f[V]dir\f[R], \f[V]none\f[R],
\f[V]mount\f[R]).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--memory-unit <UNIT>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Force memory units (\f[V]kib\f[R], \f[V]mib\f[R], \f[V]gib\f[R]).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--packages <MODE>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Control package summaries (\f[V]off\f[R], \f[V]on\f[R], \f[V]tiny\f[R]).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--uptime <MODE>\f[R] / \f[V]--os-age <MODE>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Pick shorthand (\f[V]full\f[R], \f[V]tiny\f[R], \f[V]seconds\f[R]).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--distro-display <MODE>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Set OS detail level (e.g., \f[V]name\f[R], \f[V]name_version\f[R],
\f[V]name_model_arch\f[R]).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--cpu-temp-unit <UNIT>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Select CPU temperature units (\f[V]C\f[R], \f[V]F\f[R], or \f[V]off\f[R]
to hide).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--format <pretty|json>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Choose human-readable pretty output (default) or machine-readable JSON.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--ssh <HOST>...\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Fetch system info from one or more hosts via SSH, then render locally.
Each host runs \f[V]leenfetch --format json\f[R] remotely; the output is
printed locally using the requested format.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--only <LIST>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Render only the listed modules (comma-separated).
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]--hide <LIST>\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Hide specific modules (comma-separated).
.IP \[bu] 2
Boolean toggles use a single flag with an explicit value, for example
\f[V]--cpu-speed true\f[R], \f[V]--shell-path false\f[R],
\f[V]--memory-percent true\f[R], or \f[V]--refresh-rate false\f[R].
.SS REMOTE FETCHING OVER SSH
.PP
\f[V]--ssh\f[R] lets you pull data from remote hosts and render it
locally.
LeenFetch connects with your system SSH client, runs
\f[V]leenfetch --format json\f[R] on each target, parses the output, and
prints either pretty text (default) or JSON (\f[V]--format json\f[R]).
.IP \[bu] 2
Requirements: the remote host must have \f[V]leenfetch\f[R] in
\f[V]PATH\f[R].
.IP \[bu] 2
Uses your SSH config/agent, honoring usernames/ports in the target
string; a short connect timeout is applied.
.IP \[bu] 2
Per-host ASCII art/colors come from the remote distro while layout comes
from your local config.
.IP \[bu] 2
JSON mode prints one JSON object per host (separated by blank lines).
.SS CONFIGURATION
.PP
leenfetch uses a single JSONC file for configuration, typically located
at:
.IP
.nf
\f[C]
$XDG_CONFIG_HOME/leenfetch/
\[ti]/.config/leenfetch/
\f[R]
.fi
.PP
The configuration file is: - \f[B]config.jsonc\f[R]: Includes
\f[V]flags\f[R], an ordered \f[V]modules\f[R] (\f[V]layout\f[R]) array,
and an optional \f[V]logo\f[R] override.
Use strings like \f[V]\[dq]break\[dq]\f[R] for spacers or objects with
\f[V]type\f[R]/\f[V]key\f[R] to control the output.
JSONC keeps comments intact so every option is documented in place.
.PP
Edit the file to adjust appearance, enabled modules, spacing, or output
order.
.SS EXAMPLES
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]leenfetch\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Display system information using the current configuration.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]leenfetch --ascii_distro debian\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Show system info with Debian ASCII art, regardless of detected distro.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]leenfetch --init\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Create the default config file if missing.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]leenfetch --reinit\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Delete and regenerate the config file.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]leenfetch --ssh user\[at]server\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]leenfetch --ssh user\[at]server:port\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]leenfetch --ssh user\[at]server:port --ssh user\[at]server:port\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Fetch system info from a remote host over SSH and render locally.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]echo \[dq]Rustacean\[dq] | leenfetch\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
Display system info with a piped ASCII logo generated from the input
text.
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]fortune | cowsay | leenfetch\f[R]
.PD 0
.P
.PD
fortune generates a random quote.
cowsay wraps it in a cow speech bubble (ASCII art).
leenfetch takes piped input and displays it as an ASCII logo.
.SS ENVIRONMENT
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[B]XDG_CONFIG_HOME\f[R]: Specifies the base directory for
user-specific configuration files.
Defaults to \f[V]\[ti]/.config\f[R] if not set.
.SS FILE
.IP \[bu] 2
\f[V]\[ti]/.config/leenfetch/config.jsonc\f[R]
